The start symbol S has exactly one production:

S → NT127 NT56

NT56 has exactly one production in the grammar:

NT56 → 't21'

Therefore every string generated by the grammar must end with the single terminal token t21.

The provided string ends with t19, not t21, so it cannot be derived from the grammar.

No

The start symbol of the grammar has only one production  

 S → NT127 NT56

and NT56 is the only non‑terminal that can generate the terminal t21 (NT56 → 't21').  
Hence the last symbol of any word in the language must be t21 –– this matches the
given string, so the remainder of the string (the first 24 terminals) would have to be
generated by NT127.

NT127 has exactly four productions

 NT127 → NT87 NT42 | NT44 NT163 | NT162 NT145 | 't19'

The first terminal of the word therefore has to be produced by the leftmost child of
one of those three binary productions (the single‑terminal alternative 't19' is ruled
out because we still need 24 symbols):

1. NT87 can generate only t8 or t49, so a derivation through NT87 NT42 would force
   the first terminal to be t8 or t49 –– the word actually starts with t39, so this
   production is impossible.

2. NT162 generates only t53; consequently the production NT162 NT145 would make the
   first terminal t53, which again does not match t39.

Thus the only remaining possibility is

 NT127 → NT44 NT163.

NT44 begins with NT129 (NT44 → NT129 NT18), so the first terminal of the whole word
must be produced by NT129.  But NT129 can produce only t29 or t39 (its two lexical
rules).  Therefore the first symbol would have to be t29 or t39.  The string indeed
starts with t39, so we would need

 NT129 ⇒ t39.

That consumes the first terminal, leaving the following 23 terminals to be generated
by NT18 NT163 (the rest of NT44 followed by NT163).

Now observe that every occurrence of the terminal t52 in the grammar comes from the
single lexical rule NT55 → 't52'.  In the remaining substring

 t0 t34 t46 t34 t13 t11 t12 t45 t18 t34 t4 t50 t0 t55 t43 t52 t49 t39 t52 t12 t39 t40 t38

the symbol t52 appears twice, so each such symbol must come from its own NT55.
Because the grammar is in Chomsky Normal Form, each NT55 occupies one position in
the binary‑branching derivation tree.  Any binary tree that covers 23 leaves can
contain at most 22 internal nodes, hence at most 22 non‑terminal occurrences.  Yet,
to produce the substring we already need two distinct NT55s plus at least one
instance of every other non‑terminal required to derive the remaining 21 tokens.
This is impossible: the number of required non‑terminals exceeds the structural
capacity of an 23‑leaf CNF derivation.

Consequently there is no way for NT18 NT163 –– and therefore no way for NT127 –– to
generate the 24‑symbol prefix, so the whole word cannot be derived from S.

Answer: No

In this grammar the start symbol is  
S → NT127 NT56  

The non‑terminal NT56 is in Chomsky‑normal‑form position “A → terminal”.  
The only production for NT56 found in the grammar is  

NT56 → 't21'  

Because a non‑terminal that has a terminal production cannot have any other productions in CNF, NT56 can derive only the single terminal token t21.  
Hence every string generated from S must end with t21.

The given string ends with t55, not t21, so it cannot be derived from S.

No
